WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:03.960
Foreign

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:13.740
[Music] I'm Norman Wildberger, and&nbsp;
I'm going to be extending this novel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:19.020
arithmetic of ours based on multi-sets,&nbsp;
what we might call box arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.020 --> 00:00:27.240
in the direction of negative numbers,&nbsp;
which we got at by introducing anti-msets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:33.300
a rather novel arithmetical feature that&nbsp;
somehow mysteriously parallels the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:39.600
of modern 20th-century particle physics with&nbsp;
the particle-antiparticle duality or symmetry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:46.200
that seems to pervade the physical world.&nbsp;
Perhaps something parallel to that actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:52.020
sits at the heart of mathematics as well, even&nbsp;
though it hasn't really been explored very much.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:57.420
Today, we're going to have a closer look at all&nbsp;
this interesting arithmetic with some examples.

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:03.000
So let me just remind you that the setup is&nbsp;
that we're starting now with our zero world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:10.260
consisting of two objects, not a single zero which&nbsp;
is the empty mset, but also the anti-zero denoted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:16.080
with the same notation but with a superscript&nbsp;
'a'. I'm also going to introduce some possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:22.860
variants that we could use in some situations,&nbsp;
one being just to replace the black bounding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:29.640
brackets with red bounding brackets, parallel&nbsp;
to what an accountant would do in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:39.720
black and red representing positive and negative&nbsp;
assets and liabilities. Perhaps when we're using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:49.020
a typed situation with just on a line, we could&nbsp;
also introduce braces, just a suggestion to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:53.400
give us an alternate way&nbsp;
of representing anti-msets.

00:01:53.940 --> 00:02:01.440
Then we had these two very identical tables&nbsp;
for the addition and multiplication: zero plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:10.140
zero is zero, zero plus anti-zero is anti-zero,&nbsp;
and exactly the same for multiplication.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:18.900
Curiously, especially here, this gives us this&nbsp;
unusual law that zero times anti-zero is anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:26.760
rather than zero, which contradicts our experience&nbsp;
that zero times anything is always zero. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:31.500
makes us a little bit uneasy; this is certainly a&nbsp;
different kind of arithmetic than we're used to.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:40.320
As some viewers point out, this can also lead to&nbsp;
a failure of the distributive law at this very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:46.980
elementary level with just zeros and anti-zeros.&nbsp;
For example, if we look at zero plus zero times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:51.240
anti-zero, well, zero plus zero is zero, so&nbsp;
that's going to be exactly this: we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:58.200
get anti-zero. But on the other hand, if we look&nbsp;
at zero times anti-zero plus zero times anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.200 --> 00:03:03.180
this one's an anti-zero, this one's an anti-zero,&nbsp;
and according to this, the sum is then going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:10.380
zero. So the usual distributive law, just at the&nbsp;
level of these zero objects, is not going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:16.740
valid. Now, that does not mean that the actual&nbsp;
arithmetic that we're primarily interested in,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:22.440
having to do with numbers and poly numbers&nbsp;
and multi-numbers, etc., is also necessarily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:28.800
inconsistent, but it just means that we do have to&nbsp;
be rather careful about questions of the logical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:35.400
structure of things. Ultimately, we want proofs&nbsp;
and perhaps models of this that will ensure that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:41.520
what we're doing is logically consistent. At this&nbsp;
stage here, it's exploratory, and in that spirit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:48.420
we're going to give you some examples today&nbsp;
of these anti-msets that are built up from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:55.860
this anti-zero, and also then negative numbers&nbsp;
and then intervals, integral poly numbers, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.860 --> 00:04:03.960
integer polynumbers, extending the negativity into&nbsp;
the world of poly numbers. In some sense, this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:10.260
like an assembly language approach to arithmetic,&nbsp;
you know, we're going really right down to a sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:15.780
of fundamental level here and uncovering structure&nbsp;
that's a little bit unfamiliar, even though it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:22.500
does lead to pretty familiar arithmetic, but we&nbsp;
get to look at that arithmetic in a new light.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:31.080
Last time, we saw that as a consequence of&nbsp;
having anti-zero, we should probably extend this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:38.400
anti-notion to msets very generally, so that&nbsp;
for any mset or object M in this arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:44.280
there is going to be an anti-object, which&nbsp;
we denote by m superscript 'a', which has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:50.820
the property that if M and anti-M are together&nbsp;
in an mset, then they cancel out just like an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:59.520
electron and a positron, and we just get an empty&nbsp;
mset as a result. We also saw that this m-a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:08.460
this anti-M, can be evaluated by essentially&nbsp;
adding the anti-zero to M in either order. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.460 --> 00:05:19.200
particular, this shows that the anti of anti-zero&nbsp;
is zero. Extending that sort of black-red approach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:26.340
to notation, let me suggest that we could use&nbsp;
the following sort of two-dimensional version&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:33.060
of that. So if here's an mset M, okay, it's a box&nbsp;
with a couple of boxes in it. This is an empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:45.300
box, and this box here has two empty boxes in it.&nbsp;
This would be what we would usually call one plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:53.040
alpha squared in polynumber language if we&nbsp;
wrote it out in terms of linear structure.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:58.440
There's a big mset with an empty mset there,&nbsp;
and here's an mset with two msets inside it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:04.440
If we were looking at this mset and trying to&nbsp;
understand its anti-object, so M superscript 'a',&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:12.840
then I propose that we could denote that with a&nbsp;
red bounding box. So we take this thing here and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:17.880
we copy it essentially, with the distinction&nbsp;
that the outside box, the containing box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:23.460
is now red instead of black, but the interior&nbsp;
things are just the same as they were over here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:31.800
In the linear case, that would involve&nbsp;
replacing these outside brackets with red&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:36.240
brackets instead of black brackets, but&nbsp;
crucially, what's inside stays the same.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:42.000
If we didn't have colors at our disposal, we&nbsp;
could replace these red brackets with, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.060
braces or whatever else we wanted to use.&nbsp;
I like this two-dimensional representation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:54.480
because our minds are very much oriented to&nbsp;
two-dimensional visualization and understanding,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.480 --> 00:07:00.660
and so this makes demonstrating things a little&nbsp;
bit easier for us. If we have something too&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:08.460
complicated like this, it's fine for an AI or&nbsp;
a computer, but our physiology prefers to see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:13.740
things in this form here. So this is actually&nbsp;
quite a useful way of illustrating some things.

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:22.200
The first use of these anti-objects is to&nbsp;
define minus one, or I like to write one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:28.140
bar. So one bar, or minus one, is the&nbsp;
mset consisting of a single anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:34.860
and it has the property that if you add one&nbsp;
bar with one, then you're going to get a zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.860 --> 00:07:43.620
or the empty set. The multiplication of one and&nbsp;
one bar follows this sort of familiar pattern,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:49.440
and then we can extend this negation to&nbsp;
natural numbers. So if N is a natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:56.520
then we can define N-bar, or minus N, to be one&nbsp;
bar times N. That then introduces an extension&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.520 --> 00:08:04.200
of our fundamental objects from natural numbers&nbsp;
to integers. So we create integers by multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:12.120
natural numbers by minus one. Now we have a wider&nbsp;
framework, and it's really this wider framework&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:19.920
that is a very pleasant environment with lots&nbsp;
of interesting applications. Furthermore, if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:28.080
have a more general mset, a pure mset M, then we&nbsp;
can define its negative also, M-bar or minus M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:34.680
exactly in the same way: we just multiply by one&nbsp;
bar. I remind you that in this world we can always&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:42.420
add and we can always multiply msets. There's&nbsp;
no requirement that these things necessarily be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.420 --> 00:08:46.320
numbers; those are just the top-level things,&nbsp;
but there's a whole range of different,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:51.840
more complicated kinds of objects, and these&nbsp;
operations extend to all of them. We also saw that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:58.560
another way of thinking about this M-bar was that&nbsp;
it consists of the mset whose elements are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:07.860
antis of all the elements of capital M. So it's&nbsp;
the mset of M-a as M ranges through capital M.

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:11.880
Let's do some examples of some&nbsp;
simple integer arithmetic:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:21.540
two plus one bar plus four bar. Well, two is the&nbsp;
mset consisting of zero zero, one bar is the mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:29.400
consisting of just the single anti-zero, and four&nbsp;
bar is anti-zero anti-zero anti-zero anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:33.600
When we add them, we just dump&nbsp;
everything out into a single mset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:39.600
so we get zero zero anti-zero here and&nbsp;
then a bunch of anti-zeros further,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:48.540
and then once we have them all in an mset, the&nbsp;
zeros and the anti-zeros will mutually annihilate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:54.480
each other. So say that pair will disappear and&nbsp;
that pair will disappear, and we're left just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.480 --> 00:10:02.220
with anti-zero anti-zero anti-zero, which&nbsp;
we recognize as three bar or minus three.

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:14.700
What about three times two bar? Well, three&nbsp;
is zero zero zero, and two bar is anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:21.180
anti-zero. How do we multiply these? Well, we have&nbsp;
to form the big mset consisting of all possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:28.020
sums of elements here with elements here. So we&nbsp;
have to be able to evaluate zero plus anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.020 --> 00:10:34.020
which we know is anti-zero, and there are going to&nbsp;
be six possible such things, so we're going to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:40.740
that thing, which we recognize as six bar.

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:50.760
Let's illustrate the fact that multiplication, and&nbsp;
in fact addition also, are not essentially binary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:57.300
operations in this world; they, in principle, are&nbsp;
things that can input a whole bunch of things at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.300 --> 00:11:03.780
the same time. Let's multiply two bar times&nbsp;
four bar times one bar. So that's anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:10.320
anti-zero, there's two bar, multiplied by&nbsp;
anti-zero anti-zero anti-zero anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:14.580
there's four bar, multiplied by&nbsp;
just anti-zero, that's one bar.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:23.100
So what are we going to have to do? We're going&nbsp;
to have to take an mset that consists of all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:30.060
possible sums of elements here, elements here,&nbsp;
and elements here. So I'm going to take one of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:34.680
these anti-zeros, one of these anti-zeros, and&nbsp;
one of these anti-zeros. We're going to add them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:43.860
so over here on the side, let's just compute this&nbsp;
thing: anti-zero plus anti-zero plus anti-zero.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:12:01.020
Anti-zero plus anti-zero is zero, and zero plus&nbsp;
anti-zero is anti-zero, so this just gives us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:09.300
anti-zero. In fact, more generally, if&nbsp;
we had K anti-zeros all added together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:18.240
then whether we get zero or anti-zero as the final&nbsp;
result depends on whether K is even or odd. If&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:22.200
there's an odd number of anti-zeros, we're going&nbsp;
to get an anti-zero. If there's an even number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:28.020
of anti-zeros, we're going to get a zero. Because&nbsp;
the addition and the multiplication tables are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:33.300
same, that's the same statement if we replace the&nbsp;
additions here with multiplications. So anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:38.400
times anti-zero times anti-zero is also going&nbsp;
to be anti-zero. It's clear what we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:47.040
to get here: we are going to get a whole bunch&nbsp;
of anti-zeros, a whole bunch of them, one, two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:47.040 --> 00:12:52.800
three, four, five, six, seven, eight,&nbsp;
and so the final result is eight bar.

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:58.260
Now we can convince ourselves that&nbsp;
the arithmetic that we've cooked up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:02.640
here really does obey the same rules as our usual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.120
integer arithmetic with respect to the&nbsp;
operations addition and multiplication.

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:10.920
Let's go down one level to the poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:19.620
I remind you that a poly number is an mset of&nbsp;
natural numbers. Let's look at an example. Here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:26.880
an mset of natural numbers: P is the mset 0 0 2&nbsp;
2 5. These are all natural numbers, and this has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:36.180
an interpretation in terms of more usual notation&nbsp;
as 2 plus 3 alpha squared plus alpha to the five.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:44.160
If we connect with my usual preferred notation&nbsp;
for poly numbers, like we use in the algebraic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:49.020
calculus course or that we've talked about&nbsp;
extensively in the Math Foundation series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:56.460
we can think of a poly number like a polynomial&nbsp;
as a list, a vertical list, say, typically of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.460 --> 00:14:01.800
coefficients. The actual variable itself is sort&nbsp;
of secondary; it's sort of implicit. It's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:06.240
the coefficients that are the crucial thing.&nbsp;
So here, there's a two, there's zero alphas,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:11.040
three alpha squares, zero alpha cubed, zero&nbsp;
alpha to the fourth, one alpha to the fifth.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:18.660
Let me just point out again the important&nbsp;
distinction here between this more classical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:27.060
approach to what a poly number is, namely as&nbsp;
a list, and this new point of view, this mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:27.060 --> 00:14:33.480
point of view towards what a poly number is. These&nbsp;
are closely connected in the sense that this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:39.660
here is really the multiplicity list for this&nbsp;
mset. This is keeping track of how many of each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:44.100
of these objects we have because the objects&nbsp;
appearing here are naturally ordered; they're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.100 --> 00:14:51.600
natural numbers, so 0, 1, 2, 3, etc. We can encode&nbsp;
this information just sort of by counting how many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:55.740
zeros there are, how many ones there are, how many&nbsp;
twos there are, how many threes there are, etc.

00:14:58.260 --> 00:15:06.960
But there's a sense in which this is actually&nbsp;
a more basic or fundamental object because the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:11.820
ambiguity that's appearing over here,&nbsp;
that you're allowed to add additional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.820 --> 00:15:18.840
zeros below wherever you are and it doesn't&nbsp;
change, is sort of removed at the multi-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:22.800
level because we don't have to say that&nbsp;
we're just talking about a multi-set.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:28.560
This is a subtle but important shift&nbsp;
that I do want you to take on board,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:35.760
that perhaps a poly number is really more&nbsp;
fundamentally an mset of natural numbers.

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:41.520
Now we want to enlarge that view&nbsp;
because now we have integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:52.500
Let's see what happens if we extend this notion to&nbsp;
involve integers. Here's the negation of this P.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:01.020
How do we negate an mset of P-bar or minus P?&nbsp;
Well, we just take the anti of each one of these.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:07.560
So we have zero anti, or anti-zero, anti-zero,&nbsp;
anti-two, anti-two, anti-two, anti-five.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.940 --> 00:16:17.220
That's also a poly number, a familiar kind&nbsp;
of poly number, but one involving negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:24.720
coefficients. So if we wrote it out as a poly&nbsp;
number in alpha, it would be two bar plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:32.820
three bar alpha squared. So there's really three&nbsp;
alpha squares here, but there's antis here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:40.560
so it's representing three bar alpha squared and&nbsp;
one bar alpha to the five. As a vertical list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:45.900
we could write minus two, zero, minus three,&nbsp;
zero, zero, minus one, or I prefer two bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:51.660
zero, three bar, zero, zero, one bar. Notice also&nbsp;
that I'm putting the one bar here. We're sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.660 --> 00:16:57.420
forced to here because we don't have a subtraction&nbsp;
operation, so it would be wrong for us to say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:02.520
minus alpha to the five. Not wrong, but not really&nbsp;
consistent with what we're doing so far. So far,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:07.860
we really only have addition and multiplication,&nbsp;
so strictly speaking, to be consistent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.860 --> 00:17:13.380
we probably also should put a one here. It's&nbsp;
probably a little bit more consistent if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:22.620
treat all these things sort of uniformly and treat&nbsp;
the ones the same as the twos and the threes. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.620 --> 00:17:27.720
suppose we could even go one step further and&nbsp;
write zeros, zero alpha, etc., but that would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:35.580
be going a bit too far. Anyway, this is the&nbsp;
negation of this thing here in an obvious way.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:41.400
We're also allowed to mix and match these things,&nbsp;
so we can have a situation where we have a poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:46.620
number which has both positive and negative&nbsp;
coefficients. For example, this Q thing here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:58.740
Have a look at it: it's mset 0 1-a, or anti-one,&nbsp;
2-a, and 3. As a poly number, this would be, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:58.740 --> 00:18:10.080
there's a single one, there's a one to the&nbsp;
a here, so that's like one bar times alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:18.660
and there's a one bar times alpha squared,&nbsp;
and there's a one bar times alpha cubed.

00:18:21.480 --> 00:18:31.980
What would happen if we added, say, P and Q? Well,&nbsp;
we have to put them all together in a big mset. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:38.100
there's a zero here, a zero here, and a zero,&nbsp;
so there'll be three zeros. There's a one, an a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.100 --> 00:18:44.160
there's a two, two, two. We'll put two, two, two&nbsp;
in, and we also have to put a 2-a in, an anti-two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:50.400
but that 2-a is going to cancel with one of&nbsp;
the twos. So they're going to go, so we're just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:55.620
going to have two, two, and then we'll get a three&nbsp;
and also a five. So the result would be three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:56.460 --> 00:19:04.080
plus one bar alpha plus two alpha squared&nbsp;
plus one alpha cubed. If we wanted to,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:12.540
plus one alpha to the five. More colloquially,&nbsp;
we would write this or say it as three minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:15.660
alpha plus two alpha squared plus alpha&nbsp;
cubed plus alpha to the five. That would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:20.400
be the more familiar sort of high school&nbsp;
way of saying it, but that does assume that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:26.040
we have a subtraction operation which we're&nbsp;
not assuming at this point. So that's the way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:34.920
anti-numbers generate negative coefficients. It's&nbsp;
the antis inside the brackets that are generating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:39.120
negatives sort of outside the brackets.&nbsp;
Maybe that's one way of thinking about it.

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:46.380
Great, so let's do a little bit of multiplicative&nbsp;
arithmetic with these integer polynumbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:52.080
Say 2 plus alpha times 3 minus&nbsp;
alpha squared. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:56.760
let's over here just draw a picture&nbsp;
of this thing. What is 2 plus alpha?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.020 --> 00:20:05.160
It's a box that has what in it? Well, it's going&nbsp;
to have two empty msets, so we just had that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:12.300
that would be the number two, but it also has&nbsp;
an alpha in it. What's an alpha? An alpha is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:13.620 --> 00:20:21.060
when you put a one inside this box&nbsp;
here. So 2 plus alpha looks like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:26.460
Now we're multiplying it by 3 minus&nbsp;
alpha squared. What does that look like?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:35.940
Well, that's also a box, and it has a three in&nbsp;
it. So it's the three zeros in there that makes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:41.820
the three, and then there's a minus alpha&nbsp;
squared. What does that look like? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:51.660
an alpha squared would be like when you had&nbsp;
a box here with two empty boxes inside. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:51.660 --> 00:21:00.540
we have a minus alpha squared, so I actually need&nbsp;
to change colors and introduce a red box because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:09.240
we have a minus alpha squared. So I'm going to put&nbsp;
a box here and a box here. Have a look at this.

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:18.480
If we didn't have this thing here, if we removed&nbsp;
those three things and just looked at this big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:27.360
black box with a red box inside it and two black&nbsp;
marks, this would be the negation of the thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:33.360
that we got by replacing this red box with a black&nbsp;
box. If we replace the red box with a black box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:40.200
then we would have alpha squared. Negative&nbsp;
alpha squared, you get that by taking this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:45.120
thing here and changing the color of all the&nbsp;
ingredients. In other words, replacing all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:45.120 --> 00:21:50.880
the ingredients with antis. So the minus alpha&nbsp;
squared is represented by this big box with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:57.780
red box inside it containing two black boxes.&nbsp;
We could do the arithmetic at the box level.

00:22:02.340 --> 00:22:06.540
Let's do it in a more&nbsp;
regular fashion. 2 plus alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:16.860
is an mset; it's a poly number, so it's&nbsp;
an mset of natural numbers, or these days,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:23.040
integers. So 2 is represented by zero zero,&nbsp;
and the alpha is represented by the one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:24.180 --> 00:22:30.900
We have to multiply it. Here's another mset&nbsp;
consisting of what? Well, there are three zeros&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:39.420
in it, and then there's a minus alpha squared.&nbsp;
That's like a two; we're sort of representing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:39.420 --> 00:22:44.760
alpha squared, but we have to put an anti-two&nbsp;
there because we have a minus one of them.

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:55.440
Let's see if we can do this calculation. There&nbsp;
are quite a lot of terms here. There's three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.440 --> 00:23:00.420
times four, so it'll be 12 things altogether.&nbsp;
So what do we have to do in order to multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:00.420 --> 00:23:06.720
these two things? We have to take all possible&nbsp;
sums. So zero plus zero is zero, so I'm going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:12.060
to do zero times only, so I get zero zero zero&nbsp;
two, and I'm just adding zero to all of these.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:17.580
I have to do the same thing with&nbsp;
this zero, add zero to all of these.

00:23:20.460 --> 00:23:25.020
Now I have to do the same thing with this one,&nbsp;
add one to all of these. One plus zero is one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:31.860
and one plus two alpha, so that's interesting&nbsp;
here. We need to calculate over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:31.860 --> 00:23:35.520
perhaps in a different color.&nbsp;
So what is one plus two a?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:53.340
Two a, another way of thinking about that is&nbsp;
it's one plus two plus anti-zero, right? So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:54.540 --> 00:24:03.540
anti, the anti of two. One way of saying what that&nbsp;
is, it's two plus anti-zero. So if we write it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.540 --> 00:24:11.460
this way and sort of we use distributivity,&nbsp;
we would get three plus anti-zero, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:21.300
anti-three. So according to that&nbsp;
calculation, we should have a three-a there.

00:24:23.940 --> 00:24:31.080
In terms of an actual poly&nbsp;
number, what poly number is this?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.580 --> 00:24:39.720
We get six zero, so that's six. We have these&nbsp;
three ones here, so that's like three alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:49.860
and then we have these two two-a's or anti-twos.&nbsp;
So that's like alpha squared, but with a minus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:49.860 --> 00:24:57.540
so minus two alpha squared, and there's three-a.&nbsp;
Anti-three corresponds to minus alpha cubed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.920 --> 00:25:04.800
Does that look like what we'd expect?&nbsp;
Two times three, three times alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:08.400
yes, minus two alpha squared,&nbsp;
yes, and minus alpha cubed.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:20.580
Let's do another example, say one minus alpha&nbsp;
cubed. That's going to be what? Well, one minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:20.580 --> 00:25:28.860
alpha as an mset in the more familiar way, that's&nbsp;
a zero representing the one, and the minus alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:29.380 --> 00:25:41.760
is like a one but with an 'a' here, anti-one.&nbsp;
So times zero, anti-one, times zero, anti-one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:50.460
We're going to get an mset consisting of all&nbsp;
possible triple sums: element here, element here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:50.460 --> 00:26:00.900
element here, adding them up. There'll be a zero&nbsp;
plus zero plus zero, that'll be one, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:13.800
there'll be a zero plus zero plus one-a, and then&nbsp;
there'll be a zero plus one-a plus zero. There'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:21.600
be a zero plus one-a plus one-a, that's four of&nbsp;
them, and then with the one-a, so one-a plus zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:32.400
plus zero, one-a plus zero plus one-a, one-a plus&nbsp;
one-a plus zero, and one-a plus one-a plus one-a.

00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:39.600
What are we going to get when we do all this?&nbsp;
The first thing here is zero plus zero plus zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:44.100
that's going to be zero. What's this thing&nbsp;
here, zero plus one-a? That's going to be one-a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:51.660
and in fact, so is that, and so is that, and&nbsp;
so is that. So we're going to get one-a, and so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.660 --> 00:26:58.260
is this one, so it'll be one-a, one-a, one-a.&nbsp;
So I dealt with this one here, this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.260 --> 00:27:04.740
this one here, and this one here. What about&nbsp;
this thing here, zero plus one-a plus one-a?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:19.440
What is one-a plus one-a? Anti-one plus anti-one,&nbsp;
let's do a little sum over here. So anti-one plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:26.460
anti-one. One way of thinking about what&nbsp;
an anti-one is, it's one plus anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:26.460 --> 00:27:30.960
so maybe we could write it like this.&nbsp;
That makes it clear that this is two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:41.400
plus anti-zero. Plus anti-zero is zero, so we're&nbsp;
getting two. So anti-one plus anti-one is two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:42.300 --> 00:27:46.260
It's the same kind of story with the&nbsp;
parity; there's an even number of antis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:52.860
so we're getting something that doesn't involve&nbsp;
antis. This thing here is going to give us a two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:54.960 --> 00:28:06.300
as is this one, and this one. Oh sorry, not&nbsp;
plus, just a single two, and also another two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.300 --> 00:28:12.360
and another two. Finally, this last one here,&nbsp;
three-one plus three-one plus three-one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:18.480
same kind of story, but we're&nbsp;
getting a three with an anti.

00:28:22.440 --> 00:28:28.560
If we wanted to write that out as a&nbsp;
poly number, let's squeeze it down here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:39.300
maybe in blue. This is one, there's three of these&nbsp;
one-a, so that's minus three alpha, there's three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:46.200
of these, so plus three alpha squared, and there's&nbsp;
one of these, so minus a single alpha cubed.

00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:53.760
So we've done a little binomial&nbsp;
expansion in this mset world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:54.900 --> 00:28:59.880
but now we're able to move in a different&nbsp;
direction, still staying in the world of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:59.880 --> 00:29:06.480
poly numbers, but we're going to use the fact&nbsp;
that we have integers now in a more subtle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:12.720
more expanding fashion. This leads us to what&nbsp;
we're going to call integral polynumbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:17.700
or perhaps one could say Laurent poly numbers,&nbsp;
but I'm not going to actually use that notation;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:25.380
I'm going to prefer integral poly numbers. An&nbsp;
integral poly number is an mset of integers.

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:32.940
A poly number, we said before, was an mset&nbsp;
of natural numbers like zeros, ones, twos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:37.860
etc. Now an mset of integers.

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:44.820
For example, here P, here's an mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:54.540
of integers, negative 2, negative 1,&nbsp;
negative 1, negative 1, zero, three, three.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:57.480 --> 00:30:06.540
We can now interpret this in an algebraic fashion&nbsp;
by being sort of consistent and thinking of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:13.560
negative sizes just representing powers of&nbsp;
alpha which have negative numbers as exponents.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:14.100 --> 00:30:22.440
So this two-bar here is giving us an alpha to the&nbsp;
minus two. These things here, these one-bars, are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:28.440
alpha to the minus one. There's three of them. The&nbsp;
single zero is a one, and these two alpha cubes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:35.820
these two threes, give us two alpha cubed. In&nbsp;
terms of a box, here's a box that corresponds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:35.820 --> 00:30:46.740
to this. There's a box, and it has a two-bar in&nbsp;
it. Where's the two-bar? Well, this thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:47.580 --> 00:30:54.060
is essentially the two-bar because a two would&nbsp;
look like a box, a black box with two empty boxes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:59.940
inside it. If we want to negate that, what we have&nbsp;
to do is we have to take the mset which consists&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:59.940 --> 00:31:06.420
of the antis of all the ingredients. So we have to&nbsp;
take the antis of the two involved here. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:11.880
what the two-bar looks like, and similarly,&nbsp;
the one-bars here, that one, that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:11.880 --> 00:31:18.780
and that one, are represented by a black box with&nbsp;
a red box inside. The zero is just represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:18.780 --> 00:31:23.100
with the single empty set, and the threes,&nbsp;
well, there's three, and there's another three.

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:33.660
In terms of our familiar notation for msets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:38.760
if we just look at the positive part of this,&nbsp;
maybe I should put it down a little bit.

00:31:41.880 --> 00:31:46.920
Let me write it like this. So we just looked&nbsp;
at the positive part; there's a single&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:47.940 --> 00:31:54.360
one. There's a zero alphas, zero alpha&nbsp;
squared, and there's two alpha cubes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:54.360 --> 00:32:00.240
So that would be our usual poly number&nbsp;
representation as a multiplicity list&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:07.440
with just positive powers of alpha. But now we&nbsp;
have also three alpha to the minus ones and an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:12.480
alpha to the minus two. We can represent that&nbsp;
by essentially going in this other direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:19.800
going up from this bar here. So there's three here&nbsp;
in this position and one here in this position.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:27.360
This is sort of the alpha to the zero&nbsp;
position, alpha to the one, alpha to the two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:27.360 --> 00:32:30.900
alpha to the three. This is alpha to the&nbsp;
minus one, here's alpha to the minus two.

00:32:33.660 --> 00:32:38.220
This is sort of consistent with what we're doing&nbsp;
previously, but we're kind of going in a different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:38.220 --> 00:32:45.480
direction. In my next video, I'm going to have to&nbsp;
say more about how to think about these integral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:49.920
polynomials, like what do they mean, how do we&nbsp;
represent them, or how do we think about them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:50.460 --> 00:32:57.720
Let's just do a bit of arithmetic with them to&nbsp;
give us an idea of how this works. Let's add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:57.720 --> 00:33:03.240
two integral poly numbers. Here's an integral poly&nbsp;
number, one-bar, one-bar, two. Here's another one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:08.940
three-bar, one, two, four. To add them, we just&nbsp;
make a big mset, dump everything together. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:08.940 --> 00:33:13.200
there's a one-bar, there's a one-bar, there's&nbsp;
a two, there's a three-bar, there's a one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:19.320
there's a two, there's a four. We could rewrite&nbsp;
this in maybe a slightly more organized fashion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:24.060
like this: one-bar, one-bar, one, two,&nbsp;
two. Oh, there's a three-bar, so we could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:31.080
put maybe the three-bar there. Three-bar,&nbsp;
one-bar, one-bar, one, two, two, and four.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:39.240
In terms of interpretation in terms of poly&nbsp;
numbers, this would be here. This would be two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:47.580
alpha to the minus one plus alpha squared, that&nbsp;
thing there. This thing here would be an alpha to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.580 --> 00:33:56.460
the minus three plus an alpha plus alpha squared&nbsp;
plus alpha to the four. What are we getting out of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:56.460 --> 00:34:05.580
this? We're getting an alpha to the minus three&nbsp;
plus two alpha to the minus one plus alpha plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:05.580 --> 00:34:14.760
two alpha squared plus alpha to the four. Does&nbsp;
that sound reasonable? Yes, I think it does.

00:34:18.180 --> 00:34:21.540
Here's another example, a little bit more&nbsp;
sophisticated now because we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:21.540 --> 00:34:27.360
combine these two roles of negative&nbsp;
numbers in slightly different ways.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:28.620 --> 00:34:34.440
Have a look at this thing here:&nbsp;
three-bar, one-bar, two, anti-one-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:40.620
anti-zero, two, three. First of all, let me&nbsp;
express the meaning of this in more familiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:40.620 --> 00:34:45.240
sort of poly number language. What is this thing&nbsp;
representing? It's representing the poly number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:45.240 --> 00:34:53.820
alpha to the minus three plus alpha to the minus&nbsp;
one. Without the ant here, it would be an alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:58.020
square, but there's an anti here, so we have&nbsp;
to think of it as being minus alpha squared.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:07.260
What about this one over here? The one-bar anti,&nbsp;
so one-bar is representing alpha to the minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:14.460
but we have an anti, so it's minus alpha to the&nbsp;
minus one plus one plus alpha squared plus alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:22.380
cubed. When we put them all together, let's do&nbsp;
it over here. We just dump them all together:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:22.380 --> 00:35:32.880
three-bar, one-bar, two, anti-one-bar,&nbsp;
anti-zero, two, three. What is that?

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:40.080
There's some cancellation that happens&nbsp;
because in the same mset we're seeing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:44.040
some objects and their antis. There's a&nbsp;
one-bar here, and there's an anti-one-bar;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:48.780
they're going to cancel. There's a two&nbsp;
and an anti-two; they're going to cancel.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:52.680
The three-bar and the three, they are&nbsp;
not antis; they're not going to cancel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:52.680 --> 00:35:57.660
they stay where they are. So we're going to get&nbsp;
a three-bar. What do we say? These guys cancel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:57.660 --> 00:36:04.320
these guys cancel. We're going to get a zero and&nbsp;
a three. So over here on the polynomial side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:13.860
we should be getting alpha to the minus three plus&nbsp;
one plus alpha cubed. I suppose that's reasonable.

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:22.800
Let's do a multiplication: two-bar,&nbsp;
one, times one-bar, one-bar, anti-three.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:32.580
In terms of polynomials or poly numbers, this&nbsp;
would be, this one here is like alpha to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:32.580 --> 00:36:48.360
minus two plus alpha times two alpha to the minus&nbsp;
one plus three anti, that's minus alpha cubed.

00:36:51.780 --> 00:36:55.980
At the level here, what do we have to do?&nbsp;
We have to make a big mset consisting of all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:55.980 --> 00:37:04.860
possible sums of these things, all possible&nbsp;
sums. So two-bar plus one-bar, what is that?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:12.360
Two-bar is the same as minus two, one-bar&nbsp;
is the same as minus one. When we add them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:17.280
we're going to get minus three or three-bar.&nbsp;
So we're going to get a three-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:24.900
that's sum. This sum is another three-bar. We get&nbsp;
two-bar plus three-anti. Let's think about that.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:25.860 --> 00:37:35.280
Maybe I could do that over here. Two-bar plus&nbsp;
three-anti. The three-anti you can think of as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:36.900 --> 00:37:43.920
three plus anti-zero. When we do it that way,&nbsp;
the two-bar plus the three will give us a one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:43.920 --> 00:37:47.820
so we get one plus anti-zero, which is one-anti.

00:37:54.060 --> 00:38:01.920
Which one was that? That was this two-bar plus&nbsp;
three-anti. Again, sort of an odd number of antis&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:01.920 --> 00:38:09.720
gives us an anti, but otherwise, it's like two-bar&nbsp;
plus three, so it's like one, so we're getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:09.720 --> 00:38:18.720
one-anti. We've done three sums so&nbsp;
far. We have still one plus one-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:27.420
well, that's zero, one plus one-bar,&nbsp;
that's zero, and one plus three-anti,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:32.040
that's the same story as that. The one&nbsp;
plus three is four, so we get four-anti.

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:45.660
What is this telling us? We should be getting&nbsp;
two alpha to the minus three, that a one plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:45.660 --> 00:38:54.000
two plus two a one-anti, so that's minus alpha,&nbsp;
and a four-anti, so minus alpha to the four.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:55.380 --> 00:39:00.120
Does that correspond to what we would&nbsp;
expect? Two alpha to the minus three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:12.300
minus alpha, yes, two, yes, minus alpha&nbsp;
to the fourth, I think that's right.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:14.220 --> 00:39:20.340
So it seems as if we have an interesting&nbsp;
arithmetic, but now we've used these negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:20.340 --> 00:39:28.260
numbers to enlarge our arithmetic or algebra&nbsp;
of polynomials or polynumbers in two ways,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:28.260 --> 00:39:32.640
not just in terms of adding negative&nbsp;
coefficients, the possibility of that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:40.500
but also in terms of adding the possibility of&nbsp;
negative exponents. This is a departure from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:40.500 --> 00:39:47.040
the usual story of polynomials. I'm going&nbsp;
to talk more about that in my next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:55.680
how to think about that. We're going to see some&nbsp;
new insights into what the world of polynomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:55.680 --> 00:40:00.540
and their algebra really looks like. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:40:00.540 --> 00:40:01.008
[Music]

